The dataset I will use contains information about public bikes rented, along with weather, holidays and date and hour. We want to know the demand for bikes so that the public has no problem accessing the service.

Data analysis and visualization.

First, the date as such cant be put to much use in the current state. The month information is already similar to Seasons, and the year and day arent too helpful. Therefore I chose to transform it into day of the week. We also check for NAs, and find none.

seoul$Date = as.Date(seoul$Date, format = "%d/%m/%Y")
weekday = weekdays(seoul$Date)
seoul$Date = NULL

sum(is.na(seoul))
## [1] 0

We factorize our categorical data and relevel to keep it in order and in case we need it.

seoul$Seasons = as.factor(seoul$Seasons)
seoul$Holiday = as.factor(seoul$Holiday)
seoul$Functioning.Day = as.factor(seoul$Functioning.Day)
seoul$Weekday = as.factor(weekday)
seoul$Seasons=fct_relevel(seoul$Seasons, c("Winter", "Spring", "Summer", "Autumn"))
seoul$Weekday=fct_relevel(seoul$Weekday, c("domingo", "lunes", "martes", "miércoles", "jueves", "sábado"))

If we check the hours of days where the bike renting system is not functioning, the bikes rented are 0 (obvious). Since we want to predict rented bikes when the system is working, we will remove the cases where it is not a functioning day.

ggplot(data=seoul, aes(x=Functioning.Day, y=Rented.Bike.Count)) + geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="red4")

#not functioning days not useful
no.func = which(seoul$Functioning.Day == 'No')
seoul = seoul[-no.func,]
seoul$Functioning.Day = NULL

We check the boxplot of each attribute for outliers.

boxplot(scale(seoul[,1:8]))

boxplot(scale(seoul[,9:10]))

The variables that contains most outliers are rain and snow.

If we plot each against the rented bikes, we get that most snowy or rainy days are low on demand, while it varies on days where it doesnt rain or snow.

rain = factor(ifelse(seoul$Rainfall.mm. == 0, "No rain",
                    "Rain"))
ggplot(data=seoul, aes(x=rain, y=Rented.Bike.Count)) + geom_boxplot(fill='deepskyblue') #boxplot for rain or not rain

rain_idx = which(seoul$Rainfall.mm. > 1)
ggplot(data=seoul[rain_idx,], aes(Rainfall.mm., Rented.Bike.Count)) + geom_point(color='deepskyblue4') #plot cases where it rains

snow = factor(ifelse(seoul$Snowfall..cm. == 0, "No snow",
                     "Snow"))
ggplot(data=seoul, aes(x=snow, y=Rented.Bike.Count)) + geom_boxplot(fill='paleturquoise')

Boxplot on categorical variables

ggplot(data=seoul, aes(x=Weekday, y=Rented.Bike.Count)) + geom_boxplot(fill='darkgreen', color='darkblue')

ggplot(data=seoul, aes(x=Seasons, y=Rented.Bike.Count)) + geom_boxplot(fill='darkgreen', color='darkblue')

ggplot(data=seoul, aes(x=as.factor(Hour), y=Rented.Bike.Count)) + geom_boxplot(fill='darkorange') + xlab('Time of day') + ylab('Bikes rented')

Most days are equal on demand except Sundays where it is lower. On seasons we see that clearly bikes are not very demanded on Winter, which make sense. The Hour influences the amount of bikes rented, as there is low demand during the night and high during the afternoon.

Computing the correlations it can be seen that the temperature is highly correlated with the dew point temperature, so we will remove this variable to simplify the data.

ggcorr(data=seoul,label = T)

cor(seoul$Temperature..C., seoul$Dew.point.temperature..C.)
## [1] 0.914467
seoul$Dew.point.temperature..C. = NULL

The variables that correlate the most with the target are the temperature (high temperature usually means that people will take bikes) and the hour (bikes are not rented during night).

The problem with our Hour variable is that its periodicity is not fully represented. Therefore we transform the hour into two variables for the sine and cosine, and remove the original variable.

seoul$xHour = sin(2*pi*seoul$Hour/24)
seoul$yHour = cos(2*pi*seoul$Hour/24)
seoul$Hour = NULL

Reorganizing the columns

seoul= seoul[,c(2:8, 12:13, 9:11, 1)]

Classification

On the graph we can see a slight division between two distributions. We will take that treshold to categorize the target variable in two: High and Low demand. This way, we can make apply of classification tools.

df = seoul
df$Bike.Demand = factor(ifelse(df$Rented.Bike.Count <= 500, "Low",
                                        "High"))
df$Rented.Bike.Count = NULL

Then we split the dataframe in 70% train and 30% test.

split=createDataPartition(df$Bike.Demand, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)

df_tr = df[split,]
df_ts = df[-split,]

Decision trees

We use decision trees to examine which variables it takes into account. First with a shallow tree:

control = rpart.control(minsplit = 30, maxdepth = 10, cp=0.01)
dtFit = rpart(Bike.Demand ~ ., data=df_tr, method = "class", control = control)
rpart.plot(dtFit, digits=3)

The information on the graph varies slightly depending on the data partition. We see that first it checks the temperature, since when it is lower than 7 degrees there is not much demand for bikes. Then, on days where it is higher, it compares the humidity. If it is higher than 84%, it may mean there is fog or it is cloudy, so bikes are not used. If it is lower, we consider the hour. The x factor of Hour being lower to .379 means that when the current hour is in the range between 11am to 1am, both included, there is a high probability that bikes are very demanded (0.055 is very low). Finally we use the solar radiation. It is mainly an indicator of nighttime or not, so if its night the demand should be low, and if its daytime it should be high.

With caret, we use a cross-validated tree to compare accuracies.

model=Bike.Demand ~ . # 
ctrl = trainControl(method='cv', number = 5, classProbs = TRUE, verboseIter=T)
caret.fit = train(model, 
                   data = df_tr, 
                   method = "rpart",
                   control=rpart.control(minsplit = 30, maxdepth = 16),
                   trControl = trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5),
                   tuneLength=10)

SVM

Using svm:

# already tuned, it is computationally expensive so I decided to add only the resulting parameters.

We went from 86% accuracy on LDA to a 95% accuracy with almost 0.9 kappa with this very accurate algorithm. However, gradient boosting is not as explainable as other simpler models like logistic regression or decision trees. I decided not to include ensemble on classification because the results obtained were the same as gradient boosting.

Regression

For regression, we will keep the rain and snow as it was previously, as it helps us be more specific on days it rains/snows and it doesnt create dummy variables. We split data as previously.

split=createDataPartition(seoul$Rented.Bike.Count, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)

r_tr = seoul[split,]
r_ts = seoul[-split,]

As seen previously, the variable most correlated with the target was Temperature, so we will use that for now

my.formula=sqrt(Rented.Bike.Count)~Temperature..C
ggplot(r_tr, aes(x=Temperature..C., y=Rented.Bike.Count)) + xlab("Temperature")+ ylab("Demand") +  geom_point(alpha=0.5, color='darkslategray')

ggplot(r_tr, aes(x=Temperature..C., y=sqrt(Rented.Bike.Count))) + xlab("Temperature")+ ylab("Demand") +  geom_point(alpha=0.5, color='forestgreen')

Univariable linear regression

We compute a linear regression with this variable:

linFit = lm(sqrt(Rented.Bike.Count)~Temperature..C., data=r_tr)

R2 is very low, but it gives us some explainability. Plotting the residuals and a quantile:

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(linFit, pch=21 ,bg='cyan',cex=1)

We get a very good Q-Q plot, but our model has no homoscedasticity (residuals are bigger with temperature). We can not take the log or square root of the temperature, since it has negative values.

pred = predict(linFit, r_ts)^2
cor(r_ts$Rented.Bike.Count, pred)^2
## [1] 0.307433

We get a low R^2 on prediction as well. We must use a multiple regression.

R2 = 0.59, a big improvement on what we had before. yHour seems to be not significant, but its relation with xHour is. We must establish a benchmark model to see how much we progress from it.

#benchmark
benchFit = lm(sqrt(Rented.Bike.Count) ~ 1, r_tr)
predictions = predict(benchFit, r_ts)^2
RMSE = sqrt(mean((predictions - r_ts$Rented.Bike.Count)^2))
RMSE
## [1] 662.3136

A residual mean square error of 653. We cannot use R2 because the deviation of the mean is zero.

Now on model selection, we choose all variables, the hour relation, and we will consider the square root of the solar radiation, since it is very skewed too.

linFit = lm(sqrt(Rented.Bike.Count) ~ . + xHour:yHour + sqrt(Solar.Radiation..MJ.m2.), data=r_tr)
ols_step_both_aic(linFit)

Stepwise regression

Now with caret, stepwise regression.

model = sqrt(Rented.Bike.Count) ~ Temperature..C. + xHour*yHour + Seasons + sqrt(Solar.Radiation..MJ.m2.)+ Solar.Radiation..MJ.m2. + Humidity...+ Rainfall.mm. + Weekday + Holiday + Wind.speed..m.s.
ctrl = trainControl(method = "cv", 
                     number = 5)

results = data.frame(demand = sqrt(r_ts$Rented.Bike.Count))
step_tune = train(model, 
                   data = r_tr, 
                   method = "leapSeq", 
                   preProc=c('scale', 'center'),
                   tuneGrid = expand.grid(nvmax = 2:20),
                   trControl = ctrl)
plot(step_tune)

Selecting all coeficients is best.

coef(step_tune$finalModel, step_tune$bestTune$nvmax)

KNN

The machine learning tools seem to overshadow the performance of statistical learning tools, as it can be seen when we use knn:

knn_tune = train(model, 
                  data = r_tr,
                  method = "kknn",   
                  preProc=c('scale','center'),
                  tuneGrid = expand.grid(kmax=c(7,12,15,19,21),distance=c(1),kernel='optimal'),
                  trControl = ctrl)
plot(knn_tune)

The metric barely changes with the different max number of neighbors.

results$knn = predict(knn_tune, r_ts)

postResample(pred = results$knn,  obs = results$demand)
##      RMSE  Rsquared       MAE 
## 4.2170874 0.8762061 2.9061463

Compared to previous models, R2 increased by 0.19 and the residual mean square error is a third less of what it was with the previous three tools. Now, taking the most accurate methods on classification and applying them to regression,

Random Forests

Random forests:

rf_tune = train(model, 
                 data = r_tr,
                 method = "rf",
                 preProc=c('scale','center'),
                 trControl = ctrl,
                 ntree = 100,
                 tuneGrid = data.frame(mtry=c(12)), #very expensive to tune, so i put the best parameters
                 importance = TRUE)

Best number of variables is 12

results$rf = predict(rf_tune, r_ts)

postResample(pred = results$rf,  obs = results$demand)
##      RMSE  Rsquared       MAE 
## 3.8132354 0.8983484 2.5622283

The performance is even better than KNN. Plus, it allows us for some explainability by variable importance:

plot(varImp(rf_tune, scale = F), scales = list(y = list(cex = .95)))

From the graph, it looks like dividing by day of the week was a good choice.

Not as many errors as before. Seeing how it started with the multivariate linear regression, it is a huge improvement on prediction.

Conclusions

From the data about Seoul weather, date and demand, we were able to extract important information about the features (such as the influence of daylight and temperature) and build a model to predict accurately both in classification and regression. We can assert that most statistical learning methods are not as accurate as machine learning algorithms, but they usually offer more explainability.
